Is the central bank governor too independent?
In Prague recently, developed countries' central banks have been heavily criticized.
The main points of attack are as follows: since 2008, monetary policymakers have been too active, and their powers have expanded too quickly, harming the economy.
This argument -- it's quite strange -- is popular in both seemingly incompatible ideological camps, such as libertarians and neo-Marxists, and it's completely wrong.
Critics have failed to understand that modern central banks are responsible not only for curbing inflation but also for maintaining long-term price stability.
Price levels are like human body temperature, fluctuating within a range that is neither too high nor too low without causing severe symptoms.
In fighting deflation caused by weak demand and curbing high inflation driven by excessive demand, central banks must be equally "active".
Although the battle is completely symmetrical, the public's assessment of this is strangely and seriously biased, especially in countries where people are very financially conservative.
This includes my home country, the Czech Republic. Czech savers have small savings scales, and the loan-to-deposit ratio is still far below 100%.
Czechs worry about inflation, even though the Czech inflation rate reached its lowest point in 13 years last year, and since 2013, when I became the deputy governor of the Czech National Bank, the bank has been committed to eliminating the risk of deflation.
Other common complaints about central bank policies in developed countries since 2008 are that these policies have caused redistribution effects.
Of course, that is the case, but so what?
Any monetary policy action will redistribute wealth.
Raising interest rates makes savers happy, while lowering interest rates benefits borrowers.
Importers like a strong exchange rate; exporters like a weak exchange rate.
To be effective, monetary policy must have different impacts on different groups at different times.
This is not an error; it is the essence of monetary policy.
Some critics also argue that central banks have not achieved their inflation targets in any case, so their activism is not only unnecessary but also ineffective.
Sometimes they even put these contradictory criticisms in the same sentence, as if they were accusing someone of firing blanks but causing casualties.
The reality is that advanced central banks have been successful – and indeed, remarkably successful – in maintaining price stability and monetary purchasing power during and after the global financial crisis.
If not for their intervention, their economies would have faced disastrous deflation, a sharp decline in asset prices, and a complete collapse of the financial and real sectors.
Clearly, strong action was the correct response to the crisis (what role did central banks play in the outbreak of the financial crisis is another issue).
In a system using a currency without intrinsic value, for monetary purchasing power to remain roughly constant, the money supply must change over time.
Therefore, price stability, not the money supply, is the important issue.
The central bank's balance sheet expansion reflects the depth of the problems faced by many economies after 2008.
In this context, the central bank took necessary measures to maintain purchasing power and price stability.
For them, there is no "activism" here; only the eternal mission to achieve a forever status.
If you think this judgment is arrogant, then let me provide some evidence.
People vote with their wallets.
If their purchasing power suffered a severe blow after 2008, they would naturally seek to exchange their currency (for other currencies, precious metals, or other savings means).
This is rare in the developed world.
Of course, many central banks have not achieved their inflation targets.
(Central banks typically define the ideal economic "temperature" as an annual inflation rate around 2%.
) But this is certainly unpleasant, yet it will not lead to a disaster, especially considering that the price drop is partly due to supply shocks – rather than demand shocks – such as a sharp decline in oil prices.
This shock benefits consumers and does not threaten price stability, at least for oil net-importing countries.
Consider this scenario.
A company plans to increase sales by 2%, but the manager achieves this only by increasing sales by 1% every year for two consecutive years.
Would you consider this company a failure?
Probably not.
After all, private companies' planned and actual profits and revenues can easily have deviations of 10% or more.
Most enterprises' operating environment variables are less than those of the central bank.
Given this, how do you expect the central bank to achieve precise inflation targets regardless of the economic environment?
It is essential to clarify that I am not saying central banks should not make efforts to get close to their targets.
They absolutely should.
Furthermore, they should absolutely not make inflation expectations unstable.
However, when evaluating a central bank, one needs to maintain a proper perspective.
They indeed need to stop saying unrealistic things — such as, the central bank's policy arsenal not only may be depleted but has almost been depleted.
Monetary policymakers have ample weapons and an unlimited quantity of ammunition at their disposal, which can be used arbitrarily.
These weapons have different calibers, and their effectiveness varies at different times.
Not all weapons are suitable for all economic situations in all countries.
But the central bank's ability to create and destroy money is theoretically limitless.
The central bank governor should say to them, "Enough" of their ignorant criticism.
None of our critics can explain clearly and convincingly why price stability is the wrong goal, what the central bank should be striving for, and what fundamentally different actions they should have taken since 2008.
There is a simple reason for this: the policy pursued by advanced country central banks since the crisis was the correct policy.
In fact, that policy pulled our economy back from the brink.
No need to thank me.
